&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; And one warning. Some Australians may want to keep terminal
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; unstressed &quot;Eat&quot; written as #27Eat, rather than #26It.
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; ...
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; But some of those spellings are quite idiosyncratic and
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; would, I think, make Australian QS too difficult to read elsewhere.)
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; Keep your footnote as it is.
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; I too am personally annoyed at using a terminal #26It for a sound that
&gt; &gt; &gt; to me is obviously &quot;Eat&quot;. But Read&#39;s rule about this does solve a real
&gt; &gt; &gt; issue; namely to make QS more of a morphophonemic writing system. It
&gt; &gt; &gt; is the same reason there are rules for omitting vowels when tacking on
&gt; &gt; &gt; the letter Zoo for some plurals and Day for past tenses and Ing etc.
&gt; &gt; &gt; Maybe the QM rules are in error, thier purpose is certainly never
&gt; &gt; &gt; explained. And maybe in some of these cases the burden of non phonemic
&gt; &gt; &gt; writing is higher than the morphemic benefit. Personally though I want
&gt; &gt; &gt; to clearly analyze and describe these rules before abandoning them.
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; Once the long-over-due morphemic discussion starts I imagine we are
&gt; &gt; &gt; going to want more such rules rather than fewer.
&gt; &gt; &gt;
